    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Describe your issue\n\nThere are several special cases and optimisations for `dict`s, e.g. iteration or faster lookup code. Many of them equally apply to `frozendict` and should be triggered in the same way, but were not anticipated because previously, there was only one `dict` type.\n\nI'm marking this as a \"good first issue\" because much of the work is finding the special cases and, at least in some places, changing type checks (Cython' `dict_type` builtin type, `isinstance()` or runtime `PyDict_Check()` / `PyDict_CheckExact()`) to include `frozendict` as well. We can discuss the more involved code changes if we find any along the way.\n\nRemember that the difference between `dict` and `frozendict` is the latter being immutable, so not all usages and specialisations of `dict` apply to it.\n\nSimple approach 1:\n- grep for usages of the above patterns in the code base.\n- Try to get an idea of what the code does that you find and come up with a (failing) test that uses `frozendict` instead of `dict` to exercise it.\n- Fix the test by changing the code to also handle `frozendict`.\n\nSimple approach 2:\n- Duplicate the `dict` related test files in `tests/run/` for `frozendict`, see if they work or fail (`dict.pyx` is already duplicated as `frozendict.pyx`, to give an example).\n- Also find tests that (partly) use dicts, e.g. any tests related to item lookup, get/set/delitem, by `# tag:` line, file name or usage patterns), decide (or ask) if they seem worth duplicating for `frozendict`, and if so, add the corresponding tests (preferably in the same file).\n- See if the tests fail and where, then either try to fix them or list them here and ask for further guidance.\n\nWhen you add tests, it might be a good idea to open a pull request to discuss them there, even if the new tests fail.",
